Park Avenue Trade-In



Big Deal 
By                     
 JOSH BARBANEL
 
OCT. 16, 2009




Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









IF you had  a large co-op on Park Avenue in one of those sprawling prewar buildings designed by Rosario Candela with the grand interior spaces, would you ever move? Many residents of Park Avenue never sell, preferring to let their apartments pass into the hands of heirs or estate lawyers after their last breath is drawn.But Thomas J. Edelman, a longtime oil industry executive and a founder and managing partner of White Deer Energy, a private equity firm specializing in energy, is an exception. He put his duplex apartment at 770 Park Avenue on the market recently for $11 million. A sad farewell, perhaps, to an 11-room apartment on the eighth floor of a building often ranked among the best in the city.There are the high ceilings, herringbone floors, intricate woodwork, a wood-burning fireplace and a gracious 14-by-17-foot entrance gallery.But, alas, all is not perfect in the building’s D-line. The 28-foot-long corner living room faces East 73rd Street rather than Park Avenue, though the listing, by John Burger of Brown Harris Stevens, notes some long views of Central Park. “Glorious light and charming city views abound,” the listing says.
Photo






775 Park Avenue

Credit
            Ángel Franco/The New York Times        


Cry not for Mr. Edelman, or Mr. Candela (who died in 1953) for that matter. Last year, as the price of oil was soaring toward a record of nearly $150 a barrel, Mr. Edelman bought a bigger, and arguably better, duplex apartment just across the street, at 775 Park Avenue, another building designed by Mr. Candela. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Property records show that Mr. Edelman paid $22 million for a duplex on the sixth and seventh floors, an apartment with Park Avenue views from the 32-foot-long living room, the adjacent library and three bedrooms upstairs, a total of more than 100 feet of Park Avenue frontage.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

That apartment had been the home of Frances Todman, the widow of Bill Todman, who produced classic game shows with his partner, Mark Goodson, including “Beat the Clock,” “The Price Is Right,” “To Tell the Truth” and “What’s My Line?”
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


